Gradient Descent Example¶

Generate random input data to train on¶

In [2]:
observations=1000
xs=np.random.uniform(-10,10,(observations,1))
zs=np.random.uniform(-10,10,(observations,1))
In [3]:
inputs=np.column_stack((xs,zs))
In [4]:
print(inputs[1:10])

Create the targets¶

targets=f(x,z)=2x-3z+5+noise¶

In [5]:
noise=np.random.uniform(-1,1,(observations,1))
targets=2*xs-3*zs+5+noise

Plot the training data¶

In [6]:
targets=targets.reshape(observations,)
fig=plt.figure()
ax=fig.add_subplot(111,projection='3d')
ax.plot(xs,zs,targets)
ax.view_init(azim=100)
plt.show()
targets=targets.reshape(observations,1)

Initialize variables¶

In [7]:
init_range=0.1
weights=np.random.uniform(-init_range,init_range,size=(2,1))
biases=np.random.uniform(-init_range,init_range,size=1)
print(weights)

print(biases)

Learning rate¶

In [8]:
learning_rate=0.02
In [9]:
deep,iteration,old_loss=0,0,None

Train the model¶

In [10]:
while deep <3:
    outputs=np.dot(inputs,weights) +biases
    deltas=outputs-targets
    if iteration != 0:
        old_loss=loss
    loss=np.sum(deltas ** 2) / 2 / observations
    
    if (iteration != 0) & (loss == old_loss):
        deep= deep+1
        
    print(loss)
    deltas_scaled=deltas / observations
    
    weights=weights - learning_rate * np.dot(inputs.T,deltas_scaled)
    biases= biases - learning_rate * np.sum(deltas_scaled)
    iteration +=1

Gradient Descent Example with Tensorflow 2.0¶

In [14]:
import tensorflow as tf
In [15]:
observations=1000
xs=np.random.uniform(-10,10,(observations,1))
zs=np.random.uniform(-10,10,(observations,1))

generated_inputs=np.column_stack((xs,zs))

noise=np.random.uniform(-1,1,(observations,1))

generated_targets=2*xs-3*zs+5+noise

np.savez -> saves n- dimensional arrays in .npz format, using a certain keyword for each array¶

In [16]:
np.savez('TF_intro',inputs=generated_inputs,targets=generated_targets)

Solving with Tensorflow¶

In [17]:
training_data=np.load('TF_intro.npz')
In [24]:
input_size=2
output_size=1

model=tf.keras.Sequential([tf.keras.layers.Dense(output_size)])

model.compile(optimizer='sgd',loss='mean_squared_error')

model.fit(training_data['inputs'],training_data['targets'],epochs=50,verbose=1)
# epochs represents the numberof the iterations
# verbose represents the knowledge of the output if 0, there will be no output.
